{
  "doc_id": "50064",
  "text": "The role of accommodation in distance perception is controversial. While a body of early work found negligible effects of accommodation on human distance perception, many of these results nowadays have to be reconsidered with improved experimental analyses [CITATION_1] . While accommodation can be leveraged as a distance cue, the influence of the accommodative information declines with age [CITATION_2] , distance [CITATION_3] , and with decreasing cue reliability [CITATION_4] .",
